# 📄 What is `requirements.txt`?

Think of it like a **shopping list** for your project.

When you build your URL shortener, you'll use libraries that other people built — like FastAPI, qrcode, etc. These libraries need to be **installed** before your app can run.

`requirements.txt` is just a plain text file that lists all those libraries. That's it.

```
fastapi
uvicorn
google-cloud-firestore
google-cloud-storage
qrcode[pil]
pydantic
```

---

## 🤔 Why Do You Need It?

Imagine these 3 situations:

### Situation 1 — You switch computers
You built your app on your laptop. Now you want to run it on another machine. Instead of remembering every library you installed, you just run:

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

Done. All libraries installed in one command.

### Situation 2 — You deploy to GCP
When Docker builds your container for GCP, it starts from a completely fresh Python installation — nothing is installed. It reads your `requirements.txt` and installs everything your app needs.

### Situation 3 — Someone else uses your code
Your friend clones your GitHub repo. They just run:

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

And their machine has exactly what yours has.

---

## ✍️ How to Create It

### Option 1 — Write it manually *(recommended for beginners)*

Just create a file called `requirements.txt` in your project folder and type the library names:

```
fastapi
uvicorn
google-cloud-firestore
google-cloud-storage
qrcode[pil]
pydantic
```

### Option 2 — Auto-generate it

After installing libraries with pip, run:

```bash
pip freeze > requirements.txt
```

This automatically writes every installed library into the file. Open it and you'll see something like:

```
fastapi==0.111.0
uvicorn==0.29.0
pydantic==2.7.1
qrcode==7.4.2
```

The `==` means "exactly this version". This is good because it makes sure everyone uses the same version.

---

## 📌 With Versions vs Without Versions

```
# Without versions (flexible — installs latest)
fastapi
uvicorn

# With versions (locked — installs exact version)
fastapi==0.111.0
uvicorn==0.29.0
```

> **For beginners** — use without versions while learning. Add versions later when your app is ready to deploy, so nothing unexpectedly breaks.

---

## 🔁 The Full Workflow You'll Follow

```bash
# Step 1 — activate your virtual environment
source venv/bin/activate

# Step 2 — install a library you need
pip install fastapi

# Step 3 — update your requirements.txt
pip freeze > requirements.txt

# Step 4 — commit it to GitHub
git add requirements.txt
git commit -m "added fastapi to requirements"
git push
```

> Every time you install a new library → update `requirements.txt` → commit to GitHub. Make this a habit.

---

## 🗂️ Where It Lives in Your Project

```
url-shortener/
├── main.py              ← your app code
├── requirements.txt     ← your shopping list ✅
├── Dockerfile           ← uses requirements.txt to build container
└── venv/                ← your virtual environment (never commit this)
```

---

## ⚠️ One Important Rule

**Never commit your `venv` folder to GitHub.** It's huge (thousands of files) and unnecessary — anyone can recreate it from `requirements.txt`.

Tell git to ignore it by creating a `.gitignore` file:

```bash
# Create .gitignore file
echo "venv/" >> .gitignore
echo "__pycache__/" >> .gitignore
git add .gitignore
git commit -m "added gitignore"
git push
```

Now git will never touch the `venv` folder.

